<div id="review_1984321287" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1984321287" />
    <a title="Joleen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5543196-joleen"><img alt="Joleen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1590521753p2/5543196.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1984321287?book_show_action=true">Sep 20, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joleen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joleen" href="/user/show/5543196-joleen">Joleen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/18907005-fire-by-night">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5543196-joleen?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5543196-joleen?shelf=tn-reads">tn-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5543196-joleen?shelf=civil-war">civil-war</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1984321287" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12175318368532725721"><i>Fire by Night</i> by <b>Lynn Austin</b><br/><i>Time Frame</i>: 1861-1865 (Civil War)<br/><i>Location</i>: Philadelphia, Washington DC area and Gettysburg <br/><u>Main Characters:</u><br/><i>Julia Hoffman</i> Twenty year old, single and beautiful<br/><i>James McGrath</i>: Bitter, mean-spirited surgeon for Union Army<br/><i>Nathaniel Greene</i>: Single, abolitionist pastor Julia has been in love with for years<br/><br/>Another amazing Lynn Austin book, second in the Refiner&apos;s Fire series. I&apos;d read <i>Candle in the Darkness</i> years ago, always remembered it, but haven&apos;t read the follow-up book </span>
  <span id="freeText12175318368532725721" style="display:none"><i>Fire by Night</i> by <b>Lynn Austin</b><br /><i>Time Frame</i>: 1861-1865 (Civil War)<br /><i>Location</i>: Philadelphia, Washington DC area and Gettysburg <br /><u>Main Characters:</u><br /><i>Julia Hoffman</i> Twenty year old, single and beautiful<br /><i>James McGrath</i>: Bitter, mean-spirited surgeon for Union Army<br /><i>Nathaniel Greene</i>: Single, abolitionist pastor Julia has been in love with for years<br /><br />Another amazing Lynn Austin book, second in the Refiner's Fire series. I'd read <i>Candle in the Darkness</i> years ago, always remembered it, but haven't read the follow-up book until today. Actually, the time frame for both books is about the same (throughout the whole Civil war). The first book is about Julia's cousin, Caroline, who had been spending time at Julia's family home in Philadelphia, but left to take care of things at her family estate in Virginia, which was a slave state. In the beginning of <i>Refiner's Fire</i> Julia was madly in love with the handsome, single, abolitionist preacher, Nathaniel. In <i>Fire by Night</i>, she still is.<br /><br />Synopsis - for my sake. This part will give away too much if you intend to read the book.<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<br />Julia is always trying to get Nathaniel Greene's attention in hopes he will care for her as much as she cares for him. After taking a carriage ride with Congressman Rhodes and Nathaniel to view the war from a distance, the carnage she witnessed at Bull Run made her sick (literally). The next morning, when Nathaniel is encouraged to consider Julia as a good match, she overhears him telling the congressman that he finds her "shallow, spoiled and unbearably self-absorbed". Hurt and angry she decides to do something radical to prove to him he's wrong. After much finagling and an agreement to settle down and marry when she comes home, she talks her father into allowing her to join an organization that trains women as nurses for the war cause, which is totally below her station in life. Women of her breeding don't do things like this. <br /><br />Julia's told only married women can work with men. So she lies and uses the name of her cousin Robert Hoffman as her husband, and that he's in a Rebel prison in Richmond. What she faces when she finally has an opportunity to become a nurse is the grouchy, mean-spirited surgeon, James McGrath, who does not want her there. He's terribly suspicious of her motives and does all he can to get her to walk out. She almost does a few times because the stench and horror she faces daily is nearly too much. But she persists, and makes the most of all the menial or gut wrenching tasks she has to do. The day comes when she <b>really</b> gets training… on the front. This is where she faces the true shock of war first hand, and learns that her motives for all this were not godly, and wants to truly change.<br /><br />Phoebe Bigelow was raised by her father with her three brothers, having never had a female role model. She's tall, big boned and homely (as she calls herself), only ever wore her brother's hand-me-downs, and was a better shot than all of them. Because her father is now dead and her brothers are going off to war, she's facing life alone, feeling no man would ever want to marry her. She then decides to cut off her hair, bind her chest and head to the recruiting office to become a soldier for the Union Army under her brother's nickname of Ike. There "Ike" becomes a respected soldier, and a sharpshooter in her unit. She befriends Ted, who shares a tent with her, never suspecting she's a woman. She saves his life twice in battle, but the second time is when they all hear the scream of a canon mortar coming too close. She throws herself on Ted, and is seriously injured, saving Ted's life. This was 2 days after he came upon her in a creek, shocked at what he saw... her true gender, and seriously didn't take it well at all!<br /><br />Julia's and Phoebe's two worlds come together when Phoebe is placed in Julia's tent in the hospital site at Gettysburg. As the only woman injured in battle, Dr. McGrath couldn't very well put her in the same recuperating tent with all the men. Julia nurses Ike/Phoebe back to life, but Phoebe is despondent because her best friend, Ted, is angry for her deception, wants to turn her in, and she now knows she can't go back to her life as a soldier. But what she doesn't know is Ted is looking for her, and will continue to look for her for over a year.<br /><br />Nathaniel comes back into the picture when he becomes aware how selflessly Julia has served God through her nursing. But is he the man she wants now? Or is she learning more about trusting God for her life and future? The high station in her life and the church she would serve alongside Nathaniel if they were to marry would reject her chosen vocation. It would be unseemly to be a nurse. She would have to give it up, along with much of herself to be a preacher's wife. And it's looking like Dr. McGrath is also appreciating Julia's abilities and even more... <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />This was such a good book. Clearly much <i>Civil War</i> research was done, which I loved. But more than that was how Christ is shown many times throughout the book. The sacrifice of one person putting their body in front of another's is an illustration of Christ's love for us, to offer us life when what would happen otherwise would have been death. No greater love...<br /><br />Once again Lynn Austin has knocked my socks off, and I'm in awe.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12175318368532725721" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


