    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2127775399" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2127775399" />
    <a title="Amanda Tero" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/36174922-amanda-tero"><img alt="Amanda Tero" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1592322209p2/36174922.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2127775399?book_show_action=true">Sep 18, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Amanda Tero" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Amanda Tero" href="/user/show/36174922-amanda-tero">Amanda Tero</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2127775399" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18019350645787125179">When it comes to capturing the Civil War accurately, Lynn Austin has it down. She didn&apos;t glorify the war nor romanticize people&apos;s reaction to it. It was the perfect balance of real people from various backgrounds facing hardship like never before.<br/><br/>I really liked the nursing side of the story. There was great detail given to the various diseases and cures and debates between doctors. I&apos;m not a nurse and don&apos;t think I could ever be one, so I was surprised that I thoroughly enjoyed this aspect of th</span>
  <span id="freeText18019350645787125179" style="display:none">When it comes to capturing the Civil War accurately, Lynn Austin has it down. She didn't glorify the war nor romanticize people's reaction to it. It was the perfect balance of real people from various backgrounds facing hardship like never before.<br /><br />I really liked the nursing side of the story. There was great detail given to the various diseases and cures and debates between doctors. I'm not a nurse and don't think I could ever be one, so I was surprised that I thoroughly enjoyed this aspect of the story. <br /><br />At times, I really liked Julia's story--a spoiled rich girl setting out to prove someone's accusation of her wrong. I was very interested to see how her story would end up, and when it comes to the "moral of her story," I liked it. The attitude she had when setting out was not the same attitude when she finished. But other parts of her story left me uncomfortable (more on that later).<br /><br />Phoebe's (Ike's) story overall was my favorite. There were some awkward situations and places her mind when that left me uncomfortable (again, more later), but as a whole, I enjoyed her character and personality.<br /><br />Dr. McGrath... coarse, yes; rude, yes. However, his character was the most brilliantly developed. As a writer, this was my favorite character. As a reader... let me just skip to the romance part...<br /><br />It wasn't just the romance that made me uncomfortable (romance as in the girls' love interests) but the whole way the girls thought and the depth that Austin went to sometimes to describe their feelings. Yes, their feelings were natural, but it could have been more discreet (like when Phoebe "realized" that she was a girl and her buddy was a guy). The whole relationship between Julia and the doctor was very disturbing for me--some things are resolved in the final portion of the book that, had I known one detail sooner, I wouldn't have had an uncomfortable feeling throughout the whole book. But, I didn't know that piece of information. So for me as a conservative reader, it really put me on edge--so much so that, I really didn't like the conclusion of this story. It almost gives the readers the message of, "Just follow your heart; it can't help falling in love, and even if it's not exactly acceptable, everything will work out in the end and you'll get what you want." I don't think this is the message that the author intended to put in there, but to me, it came out as a strong message.<br /><br />The spiritual aspect of this story confused me. I suppose the author was trying to display everyone in their various walks, but nothing really resolved and none of the characters really seemed to have a solid answer from God's Word. They had questions about the Bible, and there were a lot of "I thinks" but nothing really conclusive. And then, the whole issue of a woman submitting to her husband vs. following God was dealt with in a very confusing fashion for me. I'd wager to say that the view of Nathaniel Greene and Julia's father were more accurate to the era, but again, it just fell lacking to me. Maybe I was looking for more Scripture (like book one had). I don't mean to sound harsh, it's just that some big topic issues were dealt with, the characters were striving to follow God, yet there was more about "how I feel God leading me" rather than "the Bible says this" and that message can be a very dangerous one to follow (which, I know, is my personal conviction of how to root our beliefs--in God's Word, not our feelings). <br /><br />In conclusion, this doesn't quite make a 4-star book for me. It is a book that, though I enjoyed parts of it, found it amazingly historically accurate, I probably won't be inclined to re-read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18019350645787125179" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

