<div id="review_3045163671" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3045163671" />
    <a title="Mary Jo Malo" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/34435820-mary-jo-malo"><img alt="Mary Jo Malo" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1569708626p2/34435820.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3045163671?book_show_action=true">Nov 14, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mary Jo Malo" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mary Jo Malo" href="/user/show/34435820-mary-jo-malo">Mary Jo Malo</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3045163671" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16734595143989556015">One of the best ways to familiarize yourself with history is through well written historical fiction. Originally when I discovered Book #2 of this trilogy didn&apos;t continue the story of Book #1&apos;s female protagonist and other wonderful characters, I was reluctant to continue; I&apos;m so glad I persisted! This story—first told from the perspective of the South, its slaves, their owners, and soldiers during the Civil War in Book #1—is now told from the North&apos;s perspective with doctors and nurses in the h</span>
  <span id="freeText16734595143989556015" style="display:none">One of the best ways to familiarize yourself with history is through well written historical fiction. Originally when I discovered Book #2 of this trilogy didn't continue the story of Book #1's female protagonist and other wonderful characters, I was reluctant to continue; I'm so glad I persisted! This story—first told from the perspective of the South, its slaves, their owners, and soldiers during the Civil War in Book #1—is now told from the North's perspective with doctors and nurses in the horrific battlefield hospitals and shows what is happening to newly emancipated slaves. The staggering number of war deaths and casualties is unbelievable. However two female protagonists emerge, who continue to portray Austin's themes of loyalty, faith, courage and character. I mean, can we ever get enough stories of courageous, decent women who dig deep into their souls and find a path forward out of the dilemmas in which they find themselves? Especially women who can choose to continue comfortable, safe lives of privilege and tradition, women who learn through challenge and failure with integrity and authenticity. Her male characters are equally complex, some of whom resist the direction these young women have taken. <br /><br />Austin has become my favorite Christian writer, for her honesty in creating personalities who resonate from past to present in the human story writ large and small. She's an author whose knowledge of history and grasp of the simple message of loving God and neighbor inspires me always. </span>
  <a data-text-id="16734595143989556015" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


