    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1714877892" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1714877892" />
    <a title="Theresa" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18020254-theresa"><img alt="Theresa" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1362527058p2/18020254.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1714877892?book_show_action=true">Jul 31, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Theresa" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Theresa" href="/user/show/18020254-theresa">Theresa</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18020254-theresa?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18020254-theresa?shelf=christian-fiction">christian-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18020254-theresa?shelf=civil-war">civil-war</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1714877892" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11312460181178212965">Right away this Civil War fiction novel pulled me into the lives of the main characters. How clever to contrast two such vastly different women; the spoiled debutante, Julia Hoffman, and the tough tomboy-turned-soldier, Phoebe.<br/><br/>I kept thinking that the author wouldn’t be able to pull this one off. Who could believe a woman could serve in the US Army during the Civil War? I knew that that there were some indeed that did... but I questioned whether an author of historical fiction could realisticall</span>
  <span id="freeText11312460181178212965" style="display:none">Right away this Civil War fiction novel pulled me into the lives of the main characters. How clever to contrast two such vastly different women; the spoiled debutante, Julia Hoffman, and the tough tomboy-turned-soldier, Phoebe.<br /><br />I kept thinking that the author wouldn’t be able to pull this one off. Who could believe a woman could serve in the US Army during the Civil War? I knew that that there were some indeed that did... but I questioned whether an author of historical fiction could realistically portray such a thing. Well, this writer did. <br /><br />Phoebe (alias Ike) became a real flesh-and-blood character to me, and I was kept up after midnight more than once, wanting to know what would happen to her. Would she be discovered? would she make it through the war? would she ever find fulfillment as a woman or would she always be caught in her soldier-masculine role?<br /><br />Julia Hoffman did not tug at my heartstrings the same way as Phoebe did, but it was interesting watching her character develop. Julia initially *was* selfish and spoiled, ignoring the pleas of the wounded as she fled the battle of Bull Run. (I guess to be fair, I have to ask myself if I would have done the same... after all, not many of us today have been exposed to such brutal battle scenes). However Julia’s honesty about herself (and her motives), and her desire to improve through doing the ‘hard thing’ was commendable.<br /><br />Lynn Austin did a good overview of the Civil War battles, touching briefly on the major points, wins and losses, questions especially those on the Union side would ask, seeking answers for the seemingly futile waste of life. Will Dr. James McGrath ever find peace in his personal life? will Julia be content to return to her pampered, wealthy life and a proper marriage? will Phoebe be able to reconcile what she has experienced in war with a loving true God?<br /><br />Except for one or two incidents near the end of the book that were unnecessary – as they didn’t move the plot along at all --and a bit ‘over the top’ as far as believability goes (scenes that include an attempted rape and rescue although not graphic), and a predictable ending, I really enjoyed this book!<br /><br /><i>“Julia remembered James turning to her the night Fredericksburg was in flames and asking, “Do you think anyone who experiences this can ever be the same?” She wasn’t the same person she’d been before the war. She could never be that person again.”</i><br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="11312460181178212965" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review1714877892">
  <td colspan="2">
